firewall-bridge

nftables + netlink routing bridge for Linux. Python owns rules, state,
and presets; Rust is a kernel-only FFI surface.


v2.1.4 - 2026-03-26
-------------------

  Adds DNAT as a first-class action in the preset schema. Presets
  can now express destination NAT rules alongside the existing
  filter and routing actions.


v2.1.3 - 2026-03-24
-------------------

  Schema patch riding on the v2.1.2 IPv6 work.

  * Added a migration for the routing_rules.family column so
    existing state databases gain dual-stack support without a
    manual reset.


v2.1.2 - 2026-03-24
-------------------

  Dual-stack release. IPv6 routing lands end-to-end and the test
  infrastructure is rebuilt around it on the same day.

  * Dual-stack IPv6 routing in the Rust FFI surface.
  * IPv6 routing support in the Python layer (mirrors the FFI
    additions).
  * Unit test runner rewritten on the Docker SDK; legacy test
    infrastructure removed in the same pass.
  * E2E test infrastructure introduced, orchestrated through
    compose-bridge.
  * CI split into parallel unit + E2E jobs (later refined to
    three parallel runners with the actions:read permission
    needed for workflow_call).
  * Vendor artifact hosting moved from Cloudflare Pages
    (vendor-artifacts.phantom.tc, served from the dev/vendor branch)
    to R2 direct upload, after the Pages setup ran into its service
    limits. Version is read directly from Cargo.toml at publish time.
  * Workflow push triggers ignore .github/ changes (no test/build
    runs for CI-only edits).
  * Added README and Turkish README with architecture diagrams.


v2.1.0 - 2026-03-02
-------------------

  Side-of-the-house reorganization. Realizes the thinning shape
  the wireguard-go-bridge moved toward in its own v2.1.

  Python takes ownership of rules, state, and presets — anything
  that benefits from being expressive and testable in user space.
  Rust is reduced to the kernel-only FFI surface: applying
  configuration to nftables and netlink, nothing more. Less code
  on the Rust side to keep aligned with kernel APIs, more
  flexibility on the Python side to evolve presets without
  touching FFI.

  Earlier within the v2.0 line:

    * Workflow split into separate test, build, and publish
      stages.
    * Publish target moved to dev/vendor as a flat directory with
      a VERSION file.
    * Fixed _ffi library discovery to look beside the package
      instead of in dist/ (matters once installed as a wheel).


v2.0.0 - 2026-03-01
-------------------

  SQLite state + ghost mode. Breaking change.

  v1.0 carried rule and routing state in-process. v2.0 moves
  state into SQLite so the bridge can be restarted, inspected,
  and reasoned about from outside the running daemon. Ghost mode
  enters as a first-class operating mode at the same time.

  * State persistence rewritten on SQLite (replaces the v1.0
    in-process state).
  * Ghost mode added as a first-class operating mode.
  * Removed the redundant test job from the package workflow.


v1.0.0 - 2026-02-28
-------------------

  Initial release. Reorganized in v2.0; documented here for
  historical continuity.

  First cut of the firewall bridge: nftables for filter and NAT,
  netlink for routing. State held in-process.

  * nftables + netlink routing bridge.
  * Mocked _resolve_platform in discovery tests to avoid false
    matches against dist/.
  * LICENSE and THIRD_PARTY_LICENSES inventory.
